1. Systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE): This autoimmune disease can cause a wide range of symptoms, including fever, seizures, hair loss (alopecia), and delirium. 
                It is important to note that these symptoms can also be caused by other conditions, so a thorough evaluation by a healthcare professional is necessary. 

2. Central nervous system (CNS) infection: Infections of the brain or spinal cord can cause fever, seizures, and delirium. 
                These infections can be serious and require prompt medical attention. 

3. HIV/AIDS: In the later stages of HIV infection, individuals may develop a weakened immune system that makes them susceptible to a variety of infections, including those that can cause fever, seizures, and delirium. 

4. Stroke: A stroke occurs when blood flow to the brain is interrupted, which can damage brain cells and lead to a variety of symptoms, including fever, seizures, and delirium. 

5. Brain tumor: A brain tumor can cause a variety of symptoms, including fever, seizures, and delirium, depending on its size and location. 

6. Meningitis: Meningitis is an inflammation of the membranes that surround the brain and spinal cord. 
                It can be caused by a variety of factors, including bacteria, viruses, and fungi. Meningitis can cause fever, seizures, and delirium. 

7. Encephalitis: Encephalitis is an inflammation of the brain itself. 
                It can be caused by a variety of factors, including viruses, bacteria, and fungi. Encephalitis can cause fever, seizures, and delirium. 

8. Drug or alcohol intoxication or withdrawal: Intoxication or withdrawal from certain drugs or alcohol can cause a variety of symptoms, including fever, seizures, and delirium. 

9. Metabolic disorders: Certain metabolic disorders, such as diabetic ketoacidosis or electrolyte imbalances, can cause fever, seizures, and delirium. 

10. Trauma: Head trauma can cause a variety of symptoms, including fever, seizures, and delirium.
